            <div class="bio-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">The Revolutionary School</h2>
                <p class="lead">
                    The Bauhaus (German for "building house") was founded in 1919 by architect Walter Gropius in Weimar, Germany. It became the most influential modernist art school of the 20th century.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In a radical departure from traditional art education, the Bauhaus rejected the divide between fine art and applied crafts. Students learned painting, sculpture, and architecture alongside carpentry, metalwork, and typography. This integration of theory and practice created a new model for design education.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The school's philosophy was revolutionary: beauty and utility are inseparable. Every object, from a teacup to a building, should be designed with both aesthetic integrity and functional purpose. This principle—"form follows function"—became the foundation of modern design.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Despite its brief existence (closed by the Nazi regime in 1933), the Bauhaus shaped modern architecture, graphic design, industrial design, and typography. Its influence extends from the International Style skyscrapers to contemporary minimalist aesthetics.
                </p>
