                    <h3 class="timeline-title">Weimar Period</h3>
                    <p class="timeline-company">The Founding Years</p>
                    <p class="timeline-description">
                        Walter Gropius established the school by merging the Weimar School of Applied Arts and the Academy of Fine Arts. The early curriculum emphasized craft workshops and experimental pedagogy, laying foundations for the movement's core philosophy.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <time class="timeline-date">1925 - 1932</time>
                    <h3 class="timeline-title">Dessau Period</h3>
                    <p class="timeline-company">The Golden Age</p>
                    <p class="timeline-description">
                        Forced to relocate due to political pressure, the school moved to Dessau. This period saw its greatest achievements: the iconic Dessau building, revolutionary furniture designs, and the development of industrial design as a discipline. Masters like Moholy-Nagy and Kandinsky flourished here.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <time class="timeline-date">1932 - 1933</time>
                    <h3 class="timeline-title">Berlin Period</h3>
                    <p class="timeline-company">The Final Chapter</p>
                    <p class="timeline-description">
                        Under director Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, the school relocated to Berlin as a private institution. Rising Nazi persecution led to its closure in April 1933. Though brief, this period marked the internationalization of Bauhaus ideas as masters and students emigrated globally.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
